'''Adolph, Count of Oldenburg-Delmenhorst''' ({{lang-de|Adolf (Alf) von Oldenburg}}; b. before 1463 - 17 February 1500) was a [[Count of Oldenburg]] from 1482 until his death.

== Biography ==
Adolph was the eldest surviving son of [[Gerhard VI, Count of Oldenburg]]. His father, overcome by the forces of the [[Frisians]] and the [[Prince-Bishopric of M√ºnster|bishopric of M√ºnster]], was forced to abdicate in 1482. Adolph then succeeded him as head of the county of Oldenburg alongside his younger brother, [[John V, Count of Oldenburg|John V]]. Captured by the Frisians in November 1483, Adolph was released after the cessation of hostilities in October 1486, against a ransom of 3,500 [[florin]]s.<ref name=Schmidt14>Schmidt, Heinrich. "Adolf" in ''Biographisches Handbuch zur Geshichte des Landes Oldenburg'', Isensee Verlag, 1992. {{ISBN|3-89442-135-5}}, p.&nbsp;14.</ref>

Even after Adolph was released, the county government remained in the hands of his brother John V. Adolph accepted this situation and dedicated himself to the war. With his other brother Otto, he participated in the campaign of Duke [[Magnus I, Duke of Saxe-Lauenburg|Magnus I of Saxe-Lauenburg]] against the Frisians of [[Land Wursten|Wursten]], then an area of free peasant under the loose overlordship of the [[Prince-Archbishopric of Bremen]], which ended in failure in 1499 due to the defense coalition built up by Prince-Archbishop [[Johann Rode von Wale|John III]]. The following year, Adolph and Otto participated to the war against [[Dithmarschen|Dithmarses]], fighting in the army of their cousin [[John, King of Denmark|King John of Denmark]]. However, the two brothers died on 17 February 1500, during the [[Battle of Hemmingstedt]], which ended in a Danish defeat.<ref name="Schmidt14" />

