'''Leslie Ruthven Pym''' (24 May 1884 &ndash; 17 July 1945) was a [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] politician in the [[United Kingdom]].

The son of the [[Walter Pym|Right Reverend Walter Ruthven Pym]], [[Diocese of Bombay of the Church of North India|Bishop of Bombay]], Pym was educated at [[Bedford School]] and [[Magdalene College, Cambridge]].<ref>[http://www.thepeerage.com/p14057.htm The Peerage]</ref> He was elected as [[Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Monmouth (UK Parliament constituency)|Monmouth]] in [[Wales]] at a [[Monmouth by-election, 1939|by-election in 1939]].  He represented the constituency in the [[British House of Commons|House of Commons]] until his death during the [[United Kingdom general election, 1945|1945 general election]]. Polling took place on 5 July 1945. Pym died 12 days later, but nine days before the declaration of the result. He was declared posthumously elected on 26 July 1945, provoking a by-election in his Monmouth constituency. That contest was won by [[Peter Thorneycroft]].

Leslie Pym died on 17 July 1945, three days before his brother, [[Thomas Wentworth Pym|Revd Canon Thomas Wentworth Pym]], and, coincidentally, on the same day as [[Sir Edward Campbell, 1st Baronet|Sir Edward Campbell]], the member for [[Bromley (UK Parliament constituency)|Bromley]], who was also posthumously elected.

In the [[Coalition Government 1940‚Äì1945|war-time coalition government]], he was a [[whip (politics)|government whip]].

Pym was a descendant of the 17th century [[Parliament of England|Parliamentarian]] [[John Pym]]. His son [[Francis Pym|Francis]] (1922‚Äì2008) was later a Conservative MP and [[Cabinet of the United Kingdom|Cabinet minister]].

