'''Pope John XIV''' ({{lang-la|Ioannes XIV}}; died 20 August 984) was [[Pope]] from December 983 to his death in 984. He was the successor to [[Pope Benedict VII]].

John XIV was born at [[Pavia]], and before his elevation to the papal chair was imperial Archchancellor for Italy of Emperor [[Otto II]].<ref>{{Cite EB1911|wstitle=John XIV (pope)|display=John XIV.|volume=15|page=435}}</ref>  His earliest document in that capacity dates from 28 December 980, and the latest from 27 August 983.<ref>Gerhard Schwart (1907), [https://archive.org/details/MN42020ucmf_1 ''Die Besetzung der Bist√ºmer Reichsitaliens unter den s√§chsischen und salischen Kaisern: mit den Listen der Bisch√∂fe, 951-1122'' (Leipzig: B.G. Teubner) (in German), p.&nbsp;142.</ref> Queen Adelheid of Burgundy, the wife of Otto II, and Queen Theano his wife, on behalf of Otto III, wished to make [[Majolus of Cluny]] pope in 983, but he refused, and Pietro Canepanova, Bishop of Pavia, was chosen instead.<ref>J. N. D. Kelly, ''The Oxford Dictionary of Popes'' (Oxford 1986), "John XIV", p. 132.</ref>

His original name was Pietro Canepanova,<ref>George L. Williams, ''Papal Genealogy: The Families And Descendants Of The Popes'', (McFarland & Company, 1998), 232.</ref> but he [[papal name|took the name]] John XIV to [[Pope Peter II|avoid being linked]] to [[St. Peter]] himself.

Otto II died shortly after his election, his heir [[Otto III]], being only 3&nbsp;years old and unable to protect John's position as Pope. [[Antipope Boniface VII]] (974, 984‚Äì985), on the strength of the popular feeling against the new Pope, returned from [[Constantinople]] and placed John XIV in prison in the [[Castel Sant'Angelo]], where he died either from starvation or poison.<ref>Eleanor Shipley Duckett, ''Death and Life in the Tenth Century'', (University of Michigan Press, 1967), 110.</ref>

There has been considerable confusion of the [[pope John (numbering)|number of Popes John]]. There was only the one John XIV. However, by the 13th century, clerical authorities in the Vatican came to wrongly believe that there were two John XIVs and began to double-count John XIV accordingly. This led to a pope calling himself [[Pope John XXI|John XXI]], instead of John XX, in 1276.

