'''William de Alburwyke''' [[Doctor of Divinity|DD]] was an [[England|English]] medieval [[singer]], college [[Fellow (college)|fellow]], and university [[Chancellor (education)|chancellor]].<ref name="hibbert">{{cite book| title=[[The Encyclopaedia of Oxford]]|publisher=[[Macmillan Publishers|Macmillan]]|chapter=Appendix 5: Chancellors of the University|year=1988|pages=521‚Äì522|isbn=0-333-39917-X|editor-last=Hibbert|editor-first=Christopher|editor-link=Christopher Hibbert}}</ref>

William de Alburwyke was [[chantor]] of [[York]] in northern [[England]].<ref name="wood">{{cite book|title=The History and Antiquities of the Colleges and Halls in the University of Oxford |first=Anthony|last=Wood |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=X1dbAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA20|chapter=Fasti Oxonienses | publisher=[[Google Books]]|year=1790 |page=20 }}</ref> He was also at [[Merton College, Oxford]] and a [[Doctor of Divinity]]. He was [[Principal (college)|Principal]] of [[Broadgates Hall]], which later became [[Pembroke College, Oxford]]. Between 1324‚Äì26, he was [[Chancellor of the University of Oxford|Chancellor]] of the [[University of Oxford]].

