'''√Üthelstan''' ({{IPAc-en|Àà|√¶|Œ∏|…ôl|s|t|√¶|n}}; died c. 852), the eldest son of King [[√Üthelwulf of Wessex]], was the [[List of monarchs of Kent|King of Kent]] from 839 under the authority of his father.<ref>Nelson, √Üthelwulf</ref> The late D, E and F versions of the ''[[Anglo-Saxon Chronicle]]'' describe √Üthelstan as √Üthelwulf's brother, but the A, B and C versions, and [[√Üthelweard (historian)|√Üthelweard's]] ''Chronicon'', state that he was √Üthelwulf's son.<ref name=Stenton236>Stenton, p. 236, n. 1</ref> Some historians have argued that it is more probable that he was a brother, including [[Eric John]] in 1966<ref>John, p. 41, n. 1</ref> and [[Ann Williams (historian)|Ann Williams]] in 1978.<ref>Williams, "Some notes", pp. 145, 225, n. 10</ref> However, in 1991 Ann Williams described him as √Üthelwulf's son,<ref>Williams, "Athelstan"</ref> and this is now generally accepted by historians, including [[Frank Stenton]],<ref name=Stenton236/> [[Barbara Yorke]],<ref>Yorke, p. 148</ref> and D. P. Kirby.<ref>Kirby, p. 160</ref>

When √Üthelwulf became [[King of the West Saxons]] in 839 on the death of his father, [[Egbert of Wessex|Egbert]], he appointed √Üthelstan to rule over Kent, Essex, Surrey and Sussex. He is styled king in the ''[[Anglo-Saxon Chronicle]]'' and [[√Üthelweard (historian)|√Üthelweard]]'s chronicle calls him "King of the Dwellers in [[Kingdom of Kent|Kent]], of the [[East Saxons]], of the [[South Saxons]] and of [[Surrey]]". He attested a number of his father's charters as king in the 840s.

In 851, √Üthelstan and [[Ealdorman]] Ealhhere defeated a [[Vikings|Viking]] fleet and army off Sandwich, Kent, described by Frank Stenton as "the first naval battle in recorded English history".<ref>Stenton, p. 244</ref>  √Üthelstan is not mentioned after 851 and presumably died before √Üthelwulf went to Rome in 855 as he was not included in arrangements for government of the kingdom during his father's absence.<ref>Keynes and Lapidge, pp. 69, 231-2, 235.</ref> In 853 Ealhhere died in a disastrous defeat of the men of Kent and Surrey by the Vikings, and as √Üthelstan is not mentioned as present at the battle he was probably dead by then.<ref>Smyth, p. 11</ref>

